>>>>> "Don" == Don Mahurin <dmahurin@donet.com> writes:
>>>>> "Jason" == Jason L Tibbitts <tibbs@hpc.uh.edu> writes:

Don> Hi all,

Howdy Don.

Don> Is someone out there working on putting TITLE-ICON SUPOORT in
Don> FVWM?(Like there is in FVWM95)

Nope.  Or if they are it's most likely wasted effort, since I don't
think fvwm needs this and said so in the past, which is one of the
reasons that they hacked out fvwm95.

I don't mean to sound overly negative in this note, but most everyone
here already knows my reasoning.  I'll put a few here again though,
just for grins:

  - Keeping fvwm relatively lightweight and fast is a big thing for
    me.  New functionality is also good, but must be weighed against
    this to prevent bloating.  A new look provides no new
    functionality, but I am willing to bend a little sometimes, for
    example the pixmap buttons, if the code isn't too much.
  - Fvwm doesn't need to be able to look like a bunch of different
    window managers, and especially not win95 (after all, we're
    dealing with UNIX, a REAL operating system).  Granted, a lot of
    people are used to that look and feel, but I think if small
    changes can be made to fvwm to ensure that similiar keystrokes can
    be bound, that is more important and more than sufficient.
  - I don't care for anything winXX.
  - I wouldn't want to get sued by you-know-who for infringement upon
    their look and feel. :)
  - I've finially resigned myself to the fact that I can't please
    everyone, not even myself, no matter how much I'd like to.

....
Don> This whole thing leads to the bigger issue of the Fvwm - Fvwm95
Don> split.  Are they really that different that we cannot combine
Don> them.  NO.

Only the fact that I feel that a lot of the differences don't need to
be merged in, and that there are more important things to work on,
which again is what caused them to hack out fvwm95.

Certain concepts from fvwm95 could perhaps be adopted in fvwm though.

Jason> The last thing we need is yet another split.  There have been
Jason> so many (Bowman, fvwm95, others I can't remember) and of course
Jason> fvwm was a split of its own.  A bunch of diverging development
Jason> streams just slows down the whole effort.

Well, if people want to create a new window manager based on fvwm
(like Bowman did, with a change in name and docs), that's fine.  After
all, that is how fvwm started (as you noted).  Continuously updating
one or the other to stay in sync would be a detriment though, I
believe.

Jason> Now is of course not the time to try to combine development.
Jason> Now is the time to say "enough with beta versions of fvwm2" and
Jason> get it out the door.  Chuck is almost ready and we're here to
Jason> do the testing on various platforms.

I fully agree.  It's been beta way too long.

Jason> After 2.0 release I think the next thing on the list is the
Jason> style flag rewrite.

That is definitely the next thing on my plate after 2.1.0 gets
released.  I may need to make a few bugfix releases to that, but then
the next beta after that will probably be numbered 2.2.0, due to the
amount of code change needed for the style flags fixes...

Jason> Once that is finished and debugged

Which is probably going to take a little while...

Jason> it's time to think about fvwm95 and new features.  I think it's
Jason> premature to do anything else, really, until a release is made
Jason> and the style flags are redone.

Yup.  There are only a couple of new (relatively simple) things that
are going to be in 2.0.43, and I'd like to make the one after that be
2.1.0 (nothing new over 2.0.43 but bug & doc fixes).

Don> Here what I see the differences are right now:

Don> Fvwm95 has no corner decorations.  Non issue, Fvwm2 can do this already
Don> (Handle width = 0, Border width = 5)

Actually HandleWidth means "width of border if it has handles" and
BorderWidth means "width of border if it doesn't have handles".  I
don't think that the distinction makes much sense and that it might be
better to just have one BorderWidth value.  Does anyone out there
actually use different values for these?  I guess one way to find out
would be to remove it... :)

Anyways, fvwm can do it - the style option NoHandles is actually what
you use to remove the resize handles from the windows.

Don> Fvwm95 has no inner frame shadows, to make it appear like the
Don> contents are seting on some Tile, not inset into something.  I
Don> have found where the inner shadows are in the code, though the
Don> outer shadows seam to be different too.

This is probably only a few lines in RelieveWindow and RelieveParts,
which I might be willing to make an option for.

Don> The only thing that changes colors on Focus is the title bar.
Don> This could some option, or specify the Focused/unfocused title
Don> bar colors separately.

I was thinking about making an additional option for this, since I
know some people who only change the font color to indicate focus
change, changing the title bar only might be nice too, if it doesn't
take too much code & resources to do so.  I haven't investigated this
yet.

Don> And yes the TITLE-ICONS. These are mini icons that are specified with an
Don> application.  They replace the upper left Window menu button, and are
Don> beside the name in FvwmTaskbar and FvwmWinList(next release).  You can
Don> have mini-icons in Menus too.  In FvwmButtons too eventually.

As stated previously, I really don't want that in there...

Jason> The issue of whether or not to incorporate all of those extra
Jason> goodies is up to Chuck.

Do not adjust your sets...I have taken control... :)

Jason> I think that generalizing things like title and border
Jason> appearance even further can't hurt and might not bloat things a
Jason> bit.

No, it shouldn't be too bad, but that still isn't a reason to go
overboard with it.  A few of little changes can add up to a lot.  But
as I mentioned above, I am willing to look into a few of them
(probably enough to make most people happy).  Some of them would
should probably be global options instead of Style options though, to
help save on memory.  Again, investigations will occur...

Jason> Pixmaps in the title bar can't be more complex than the current
Jason> system,

Do you mean Andrew's patch for the focused & unfocused title bar
pixmaps, or the mini-icon as button one?  The former might not be too
bad, but I'm still thinking about it...

Jason> though I agree with Chuck that it's not fvwm's place to do any
Jason> kind of scaling or image manipulation.

Definitely.

Well, time for me to go.
Chuck

