CH> overboard with it.  A few of little changes can add up to a lot.

I was thinking that after you reach a certain level of complexity (piles of
window decoration parameters) it becomes worthwhile to generalize things.
Say you assign each decoration a number and instead of looking in some
bizarre variable you use an array reference.  At that point it becomes
trivial (and essentially free) to replace every hardcoded border and shadow
width with a lookup.  You lose some ease in configurability, though,
because you have to remember numbers instead of names.  Hooray for #define,
I suppose.

CH> Some of them would should probably be global options instead of Style
CH> options though, to help save on memory.

Does anyone really make some windows look vastly different than others?  I
can see having different colors, but not different border widths and
shading.

