No, you aren't confused, that's what I don't want to do.  Making the
button styles per window attributes will add quite a bit to each
window structure.  I'd rather keep that global.

Jason> Allowing pixmaps instead of the current vectorized buttons is
Jason> just icing on the cake.

Pixmaps can currently be used instead of the regular buttons, but they
are global values.

Jason> I can easily see how having some easy means of identifying what
Jason> a window contains would be useful; the icon texts for my xterms
Jason> contain the current working directory, not "XTerm".  A little
Jason> icon besides that would make it a bit easier when I have twenty
Jason> windows open.

So, perhaps a way to allow the icons to be drawn inside the icon text
box (much like the menus) could be made.  It would still be specified
as part of the style command (IconBeside/IconAbove), and after the
style flag rewrite would only require one bit to say to draw it above
the icon text or beside it.  Then you could have something like:

            Style "XTerm" Icon mini.xterm.xpm, IconBeside

or maybe:

                Style "XTerm" MiniIcon mini.xterm.xpm

to have one directive specify both (Icon <xpm> implies above, MiniIcon
<xpm> implies beside, last one specified wins).

Now, if the latter one were used, I *might* allow an extra pixmap
pointer to be stored in the window structure, so both a mini icon and
normal icon could be stored, and then *maybe* have a way in the
ButtonStyle directive to access that mini icon as one of the buttons.

I can't believe I just typed that...

But, it would allow for one per window xpm button without taking up
too much additional memory and fvwm wouldn't have to do any work to
create it.  Communicate it with the rest of the window info and
modules have access to it...

Jason> I think that generalizing things like title and border appearance
Jason> even further can't hurt and might not bloat things a bit.

CH> No, it shouldn't be too bad, but that still isn't a reason to go
CH> overboard with it.  A few of little changes can add up to a lot.

Jason> I was thinking that after you reach a certain level of
Jason> complexity (piles of window decoration parameters) it becomes
Jason> worthwhile to generalize things.
....

Perhaps, yes.  But, are piles of window decoration parameters
necessary?  That's what I was getting at.  I just want to be careful
about what's added.

CH> Some of them would should probably be global options instead of Style
CH> options though, to help save on memory.

Jason> Does anyone really make some windows look vastly different than
Jason> others?  I can see having different colors, but not different
Jason> border widths and shading.

If people want different colors, I can see people wanting different
widths and shadings too...

Jason> Pixmaps in the title bar can't be more complex than the current
Jason> system,

CH> Do you mean Andrew's patch for the focused & unfocused title bar
CH> pixmaps, or the mini-icon as button one?  The former might not be too
CH> bad, but I'm still thinking about it...

Jason> I meant that allowing pixmaps as title-bar buttons has got to
Jason> be easier than the vector-style method fvwm uses now.  Then
Jason> again, the vector method is nice because the buttons can be
Jason> scaled....

As of the current beta (2.0.42) title bar buttons can be pixmaps, just
not on a per window basis (global only).  I incorporatted Andrew's
patch for that.

BTW - I was thinking of an easier way to specify the vectors of the
normal buttons.  Something like:

  # Big square:
  ButtonStyle 2 Vectored HL(10,10,90,10) SH(90,10,90,90) SH(90,90,10,90) \
                         HL(10,90,10,10)

Where HL -> draw in Highlight color, SH -> draw in Shadow color, and
it draws in that color from x1,y1 to x2,y2 (percentage values, of
course).  Might need the number of lines specified in there too (right
after the Vectored keyword).

Of course, the old style would be available as well.

